<p>So gold is best understood as <strong>an inflation-sensitive crisis asset</strong>, not a mechanical inflation hedge. It responds less to published CPI than to the fear that inflation will persist, policy will lag, or governments will tolerate currency erosion. That is why households in chronically unstable economies have often held gold as monetary insurance. Its reputation was built not only in U.S. inflation cycles, but in places where trust in paper money repeatedly broke down.</p>
